article.description: Junior Harrington scored a season-high 19 points and Nene Hilario added 16 on 8-of-10 shooting and four steals as the Nuggets halted their 14-game losing streak with a 98-92 triumph over the Miami Heat.
article.headline: Youth movement sends Nuggets past Heat
article.linkText: The kids are all right, at last: Nuggets end 14-game skid
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- The Denver Nuggets used youth to snap a 14-game losing streak. Rookie Junior Harrington, 22, scored a career-high 19 points and 20-year-old Nene Hilario added 16 as the Denver Nuggets beat the Miami Heat 98-92 Saturday night to snap a 14-game losing streak. "We've had a lot of good performances from a lot of young players,'' said first-year Denver coach Jeff Bzdelik, who acknowledged that the losing streak had been "difficult.'' But he refused to let his young team get down on themselves. "As I said many times, successful people don't get frustrated or discouraged,'' Bzdelik said. The losing streak was still on the players' minds, however. "I don't think it was a monkey on our backs, it was a piano,'' Juwan Howard said. The Nuggets also ended a 16-game road losing streak dating back to Jan. 3 with the franchise's first victory in Miami since 1994. "For the first time, instead of letting a lead evaporate, we built on it. That's a real positive. It feels good to win, period. I'll just leave it at that,'' Bzdelik said. Denver bounced back after scoring only nine points in the first quarter, tallying at least 28 in the each of the next three quarters. A 12-0 run late in the fourth quarter cemented the rare win. Howard had 12 points and eight rebounds, and reserve Shammond Williams scored seven of his 11 points in the fourth quarter. Hilario shot a 7-for-7 from the floor before missing a dunk with 5:23 remaining. He finished 8-of-10. "A lot of games we have lost were like today, when we played really hard,'' Hilario said through his interpreter. "It was difficult to accept all those games we did lose. Today was a great feeling because we won.'' Rasual Butler led the Heat with 22 points, and Brian Grant had 16 points and 16 rebounds for his sixth straight double-double -- a career high. Mike James added 14 off the bench. "The were desperate and we were desperate,'' Butler said. "But they did more things right than we did.'' The Heat were in the second night of back-to-back home games, while the Nuggets spent their last few days engaging in leisure activities in Naples, Fla. "We were coming off a back-to-back and I thought we could have a fun time together as a group, away from the game,'' Bzdelik said.

Game notes
Bzdelik is 2-0 against his former boss, Pat Riley. ... When shooting 50 percent or better this season, the Nuggets are 4-1. ... Sean Marks left the game with a left elbow strain after getting tangled up with Hilario in the fourth quarter. ... The nine points given up by the Heat in the first quarter tied a season low for points allowed in a quarter.
